metadata.name: A Clock #249
metadata.description:
This generative token is based on a project I originally coded in late 2014, possibly my first creative project in JavaScript during graduate school at NYU ITP, which has run here since then: https://rossgoodwin.com/clock

The text in this case is not generated, but rather (legally) snipped from public domain e-books on Project Gutenberg (https://gutenberg.org/), and recontextualized as a real-time clock.

The editions vary in color palette and font choice, each with unique text for every minute determined by the clock's unique hash. For nearly all word/phrase blocks in the template system, there exist 512 possible excerpts you could receive, and countless possible combinations thereof. Additionally, 16 possible color palettes, 8 possible fonts, and many bezel types will determine your clock's visual appearance.

Unlike my original 2014 iteration, I wrote this clock in Vanilla JS with zero dependencies. (Largely, that's thanks to eight additional years of programming experience.) As a result, it's faster (once loaded) and more responsive as well.

metadata.name: HOWL.camera #102
metadata.description:
Created with the permission and endorsement of Allen Ginsberg's estate, enabled by theVERSEverse, this work channels Ginsberg's iconic poem HOWL through a dynamic ASCII lens.

Written by Ross Goodwin using 54 of Ginsberg's original photographs and a Markov language model of HOWL in vanilla JS. Each edition shifts from the minter's chosen photograph after 10 seconds into pure ASCII noise, eventually devolving into chaotic Markov fragments.

60% of mint and royalty proceeds will be donated to benefit victims of the recent Los Angeles fires.

https://howl.camera

metadata.name: CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE #258
metadata.description:
1 of 5 in CENTURY-XXX, Series 2
Edition of 1000

Tribute to Herbert W. Franke
“In Honor of the Dinosaur of Computer Art” 

Herbert W. Franke, a pioneer of computer art, passed away on July 16, 2022 at the age of 95. CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE is an homage to Franke’s MONDRIAN software developed for the Texas Instruments TI 99/4 home computer in 1979, and it’s a fundraiser to digitize his archive:

“Our goal is to raise 20,000 Euro so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. If we raise more money, it will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.” 

Each frame, a single “pixel” is added to the CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE image. When the software first loads, 100,000 frames are run in the background to start things off. Keep it running for hours or days to see it transform entirely — it’s an “infinite animation.”

metadata.name: reborn #154
metadata.description:
This is an album of cities too ideal to ever materialise.

It consists of 256 algorithmically generated plans that resemble drawings of Vincenzo Scamozzi, Pietro Cataneo, Filarete and other theorists of the Italian Renaissance. The cities differ in size, the grid of the streets, the landscape around them and the people that inhabit their utopian walls. They carry names that are Italian exonyms of real European cities, drawing a vision of a different world that enacts a mixture of military perfection with social superiority. Flawless, harmonious, unconquerable and utterly impossible.

History brought us many theories about ideal cities, but very few examples exist today. Italian Palmanova or Polish Zamość are the few to remind us how hard it is to shape reality according to ideals. When confronted with the material world, its idealism becomes the city's grates foe.

To zoom, press a mouse button over the image or touch the screen. To pan, keep the mouse pressed and move it around.

metadata.name: Uninhabitable #118
metadata.description:
Uninhabitable is a generative system built only from ellipses. The process of playing with different geometric and trigonometric disruptions gives rise to four different compositions which seek to evoque living constructions and environments. Besides the shape itself and its related distortion, the stroke weight of the lines plays a meaningful role in the piece. Following a discrete range [0.01,0.1,1] the weight reveals the process allowing the viewer to realize the trace of the huge amount of lines in each piece. This back and forth between scales and context is, while kind of stripping the code, part of my continuing interest on understanding the -usually- crazy paths of machines' way of thinking.

Press "h" to see it and high resolution and refresh to get back to the initial state. Press "h" to save it.

Uninhabitable is an original work by Iskra Velitchkova. 2021.

metadata.name: The Soul of Flowers #17
metadata.description:
The Soul of Flowers: An Ode to Algorithmic Impressionism

In the tapestry of "The Soul of Flowers," the digital realm blossoms under the touch of algorithmic impressionism, weaving a dreamscape where art diverges into uncharted flora. Inspired by the ethereal interplay between dreams and reality, this masterpiece conjures flowers that dwell not in earthly gardens but in the imagination's boundless fields.

Each bloom, a digital mirage, mirrors the complexity of human perception, capturing the myriad souls in its petals. Here, flowers are not merely seen; they are felt, as they embody the diverse essences of life, painted in strokes of unseen colors and shapes.

"The Soul of Flowers" is a digital garden where each flower narrates its own poetic story, a fusion of art and technology that invites viewers to wander through a realm of beauty, redefining the boundaries between the virtual and the real.

metadata.name: NS2: GROWTH #13
metadata.description:
Grow...
Nature...
Click...

Second part of a diptych: NS1 + NS2

Once built, the "Non Spaces" were filled with life and eventually abandoned. Nature then became the new inhabitant of those places.

Instructions:

Use the HASH feature of the NS1:SKETCH as a parameter to generate its counterpart filled with vegetation.

There is only one parameter to introduce: HASH.

The minter will generate a random, new NS building if no parameter is introduced.

S: save PNG image
R: generate a 4000-pixel image

Miami, US, 2023
Original piece by Ismahelio

metadata.name: ASSEMBLING MACHINE #91
metadata.description:
The machine never sleeps.
Build. Construct. Develop. Create. Form. Produce. Generate. Repeat.
---------------
Collectors at the highest tier (125 tez) may claim a signed 8”x10” print of their mint. Please look for details about prints on Twitter (@teaboswell), or contact me directly
---------------
CONTROLS:
A - Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)
S - Download image
Double tap (mobile) - Download image
1-6 - Modify scale (1 = default, 2048 x 2730px, 6 = maximum, 12288 x 16380px (very performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F - Fit to current screen size
G - Toggle grain overlay
L - Toggle background grid lines
B - Cycle border sizes (0 -> 100 -> 200 -> 300px)

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)
---------------
